body:
I'm simulating a module that uses packed structs in its interface and attempting to test that module in C++. E.g.:

```systemverilog
typedef packed struct {
  logic a;
  logic b;
} foo_t;

module bar(
   foo_t foo;
)
endmodule
```

I was initially expecting to be able to be able to do something in C++ like
```c++
Vbar uut{};
uut.foo.a = 1;
```

But it appears that Verilator only defines the interface in terms of vectors. I couldn't find any reference to mask/match/shift information or any struct I could cast the vector to in order to make accessing the fields in the struct easier.

Am I missing something? Is there a best practice for this kind of interface?

If all else fails, I'll create my own representation of the fields and cast back/forth, but that feels super ugly and error prone, mostly because it's not connected to the verilog header and could get out of sync.
